Month = {JUN},
Abstract = {BACKGROUNDUnderstanding interactions between biocontrol agents and their
   pest hosts under climate change should assist implementation of
   biocontrol strategies, by identifying appropriate biocontrol agents for
   release or determining the optimal timing of releases. Species
   distribution models (SDMs) were applied to evaluate the distributions of
   Trichogramma ostriniae and its native host, Ostrinia furnacalis, in
   southeastern Asia, and a non-native host, Ostrinia nubilalis, in a novel
   range, North America, using MAXENT and CLIMEX modelling approaches.
   RESULTSThe models led to similar predictions about the expected
   distribution of the two species in Asia, and emphasized likely
   mismatches between host and natural enemy. Trichogramma ostriniae was
   predicted to occur in the summer corn region of China, with distribution
   limits linked to its sensitivity to cold, seasonality of radiation and
   precipitation. The modelled Ostrinia nubilalis distribution overlapped
   with the main corn production areas of the northeastern USA and Canada;
   temporary/seasonal suitable habitat was also predicted across the
   southeastern USA. Climate change scenarios are predicted to favour T.
   ostriniae over its hosts in northeastern China and North America.
   CONCLUSIONThe modelling approaches used here proved useful for assessing
   environmental factors linked to an egg parasitoid and its lepidopteran
   hosts and identifying areas potentially suitable for inundative
   releases. (c) 2017 Society of Chemical Industry},
