Abstract = {Reproduction involves high energetic costs which are related to
   behaviour and gamete production. In females energy allocation to gamete
   production has been well documented. However, estimations of male
   investment in seminal material are scarce. The present study aims to
   assess and compare male investment in four brachyuran species by
   determining biochemical substrates present in the vasa deferentia to
   subsequently estimate energetic investment during the reproductive
   cycle. We identified two groups with contrasting energy investments. Two
   species, Homalaspis plana and Romaleon setosum, showed high investment
   due to significant quantities of proteins and lipids. Both species are
   characterised by large and complex vasa deferentia, and the formation of
   a remarkably large sperm plug deposited to the female after copulation
   as a sperm competition avoidance strategy. In contrast, Metacarcinus
   edwardsii and Taliepus dentatus invested little energy in their
   smaller-sized and simpler vasa deferentia. Morpho-functional traits may
   play a key role in determining the investment, which may also be
   influenced by mechanisms (i.e. mating tactics) to prevent sperm
   competition and the intensity of polygyny. This study emphasises the
   high amount of energy males invest in seminal material and highlights
   the diversity of mating strategies in Brachyura, which are reflected
   even on the physiological level.},
